    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1942-03-21T00:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1942-03-21T00:00:00-05:00" n="620"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d620">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">811.20 Defense(M)Peru/64: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Peru</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Norweb</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Lima</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1942-03-21T00:00:00-05:00"
                            >March 21, 1942—midnight</date>.<lb/>[Received March 22—8:40
                        a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>284. Reference Department’s 227, March 18, 1 p.m. The Minister of Finance<note
                        n="3" xml:id="d620fn3">David Dasso.</note> was favorably impressed with the
                    proposal of the Rubber Reserve Company. Since he will arrive in Washington
                    during the first days of April he stated that the matter will be discussed in
                    detail with the corresponding authorities there.</p>
                <p>His principal observations were to the effect that an over-all agreement with the
                    United States would be preferable to a contract with any of the other American
                    Republics; and that he will want to discuss the subject of establishing a tire
                    factory in Peru which has been contemplated for around 2 years.</p>
                <p>Having read the Brazilian agreement in detail Mr. Dasso this morning compared the
                    price difference between the Peruvian offer and the Brazilian contract and
                    expressed the wishes that the American Government study the possibility of
                    offering Peru a contract identical with Brazil’s. He remarked further that
                    present plans contemplate considerable shipments from the west coast of Peru and
                    that he would like to have also this point receive consideration prior to his
                    arrival in Washington.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Norweb</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
